# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asaph-hall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asaph-hall/101429-1998-vf31] Spectroscopic observations through 2007 indicate that it has a large proportion of metal and achondrites on its surface (either with or without a mesosiderite contribution); which could also indicate that the surface regolith has undergone space weathering.
[src:asaph-hall/101429-1998-vf31] These observations also reveal differences in the spectra with 5261 Eureka, suggesting they may not be related to each other after all.
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] Its orbit is very stable and is large enough that the Yarkovsky effect will not affect its orbit.
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] Due to similarity in the measured brightness of (121514) 1999 UJ7 with other Martian trojans, it is thought to be a small asteroid with an effective diameter on the order of 1 kilometer (0.62 mi).
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] Its spectrum suggests that it is an X-type asteroid, which is different from 5261 Eureka and 1998 VF31, and is somewhat puzzling since different mineral compositions suggest different origins for the two groups of asteroids.
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] The long lifetime of the orbits for these asteroids makes the possibility of one or more of them being interlopers unlikely, however.
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] This suggests that either one or more of the Martian trojans was captured in such a way as to give it a long-term stable orbit (and it is therefore not a primordial Martian asteroid), or that some fusion or combination of previous asteroids resulted in the presently observed ones.
[src:asaph-hall/121514-1999-uj7] The Yarkovsky effect may provide a potential capture mechanism but not enough is known about the shapes of these objects to provide a useful Yarkovsky model.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] The asteroid was discovered on 20 November 2007 by Andrea Boattini of the NASA-funded Catalina Sky Survey on Mount Lemmon, near Tucson, Arizona, United States, using a 1.5-meter telescope.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] It was discovered in the constellation Taurus at an apparent magnitude of +20.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] This is about 400,000 times fainter than most people can see with the naked eye on a dark night far from city lights.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] It was discovered nineteen days after passing near Earth.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] By the time it arrived at Mars it had an apparent magnitude of roughly +26 and therefore appeared over 100 times fainter than at the time of discovery.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] 2007 WD5 orbits the Sun at a distance of 2.46 astronomical units.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] The orbit's eccentricity is 0.59 and its inclination is 2.4°.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] This trend of increasing probability of impact followed by a dramatic decrease is typical as uncertainties are gradually reduced.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] In December 2004, a similar trend was observed with 99942 Apophis where the predicted probability of impact with Earth in 2029 at one point reached as high as 2.7%.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] If the asteroid had collided with Mars, it would have hit with a velocity of about 13.5 km/s (8.4 miles per second), and would have produced an explosion equivalent to about 3 megatons of TNT.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] Due to the thin atmosphere of Mars, it was predicted that the asteroid would have reached the surface intact and blasted out a crater approximately 0.8 km (0.5 mi) in diameter.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] A crater this size would be equal to the size of the Meteor Crater in Arizona, United States.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] NASA officials say if it had hit Mars, it would have done so north of the location of the *Opportunity* rover.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] 2007 WD5 is roughly the size of the cometary object that caused the Tunguska event in 1908, in remote central Siberia, Russia.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] Due to the Earth's greater gravity, an impact with the power of Tunguska is expected to occur once every few hundred years.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] Since Mars has only 1/10 the mass to attract objects, these types of impacts occur roughly every one thousand years on Mars.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] In July 2003, the asteroid passed within 0.012 AU of Mars.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] The exact fate of 2007 WD5 following the January 2008 Mars encounter is unknown although it likely passed Mars at a distance of 6.5 Mars radii.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] Mars, unlike Jupiter, is not big enough to eject the asteroid from the Solar System; however, the gravitation effect from the encounter on the asteroid's trajectory is uncertain and the asteroid is currently considered 'lost'.
[src:asaph-hall/2007-wd5] Assuming 2007 WD5 passed Mars safely, its low inclination to the ecliptic of only 2.3 degrees and high eccentricity of 0.6 could cause it to swing close to Mars or Earth for years or decades into the future.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] 2007 NS2 was discovered on 14 July 2007, by the Observatorio Astronómico de La Sagra.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Its orbit is characterized by low eccentricity (0.054), moderate inclination (18.6°) and a semi-major axis of 1.52 AU.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Upon discovery, it was classified as Mars-crosser by the Minor Planet Center.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Its orbit is well determined as it is currently (March 2013) based on 87 observations with a data-arc span of 4,800 days.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] 2007 NS2 has an absolute magnitude of 17.8, which gives a characteristic diameter of 870 m.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Jean Meeus suspected that 2007 NS2 was a Mars Trojan, and this was confirmed by Reiner Stoss's analysis of two sets of observations dating from 1998 on the MPC database.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] It was confirmed to be a Mars Trojan numerically in 2012.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Recent calculations confirm that it is a stable L5 Mars Trojan asteroid with a libration period of 1310 years and an amplitude of 14°.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] These values as well as its short-term orbital evolution are similar to those of 5261 Eureka.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Out of all known Mars Trojans, it currently has the smallest relative (to Mars) semimajor axis, 0.000059 AU.
[src:asaph-hall/311999-2007-ns2] Long-term numerical integrations show that its orbit is very stable on Gyr time-scales (1 Gyr = 1 billion years).
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] Long-term numerical integration shows that the orbit is stable.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] Innanen and Seppo Mikkola note that "contrary to intuition, there is clear empirical evidence for the stability of motion around the L4 and L5 points of all the terrestrial planets over a timeframe of several million years".
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] Since the discovery of 5261 Eureka, the Minor Planet Center has recognized three other asteroids as Martian trojans: (121514) 1999 UJ7 at the L4 point, (101429) 1998 VF31 at the L5 point, and (311999) 2007 NS2, also at the L5 point.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] At least five other asteroids in near-1:1 resonances with Mars have been discovered, but they do not exhibit trojan behavior.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] Due to close orbital similarities, most of the other, smaller, members of the L5 group are hypothesized to be fragments of 5261 Eureka that were detached after it was spun up by the YORP effect (consistent with its rotational period of 2.69 h).
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] The infrared spectrum for 5261 Eureka is typical for an A-type asteroid, but the visual spectrum is consistent with an evolved form of achondrite called an angrite.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] A-class asteroids are tinted red in hue, with a moderate albedo.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] The asteroid is located deep within a stable Lagrangian zone of Mars, which is considered indicative of a primordial origin—meaning the asteroid has most likely been in this orbit for much of the history of the Solar System.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] On 28 November 2011, a natural satellite of 5261 Eureka was found.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] This unnamed moon is about 0.46 km in diameter and orbits 2.1 km from Eureka.
[src:asaph-hall/5261-eureka] The satellite's existence was announced in September 2014.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:asaph-hall/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:asaph-hall/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall was born in Goshen, Connecticut, the son of Asaph Hall II (1800–42), a clockmaker, and Hannah Palmer (1804–80).
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] His paternal grandfather Asaph Hall I (June 11, 1735 – March 29, 1800) was a Revolutionary War officer and Connecticut state legislator.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] His father died when he was 13, leaving the family in financial difficulty, so Hall left school at 16 to become an apprentice to a carpenter.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] He later enrolled at the New-York Central College in McGrawville, New York, where he studied mathematics.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] There he took classes from an instructor of geometry and German, Angeline Stickney.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] In 1856, Hall took a job at the Harvard College Observatory in Cambridge, Massachusetts, and turned out to be an expert computer of orbits.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall became assistant astronomer at the US Naval Observatory in Washington, D.C. in 1862, and within a year of his arrival he was made professor.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] On June 5, 1872 Hall published an article entitled "On an experimental determination of $\pi$ " in the journal *Messenger of Mathematics*.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] In this article, Hall reported the results of an experiment in random sampling that Hall had persuaded his friend, Captain O.C.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Fox, to perform when Fox was recuperating from a wound received at the Second Battle of Bull Run.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] The experiment involved repetitively throwing at random a fine steel wire onto a plane wooden surface ruled with equidistant parallel lines.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] An approximation of $\pi$ was then computed as $2ml/an$ , where m is the number of trials, l is the length of the steel wire, a is the distance between parallel lines, and n is the number of intersections.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] This paper, an experiment on Buffon's needle problem, is a very early documented use of random sampling (which Nicholas Metropolis would name the Monte Carlo method during the Manhattan Project of World War II) in scientific inquiry.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] In 1875 Hall was given responsibility for the USNO 26-inch (66-cm) telescope, the largest refracting telescope in the world at the time.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] It was with this telescope that he discovered Phobos and Deimos in August 1877.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall also noticed a white spot on Saturn which he used as a marker to ascertain the planet's rotational period.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] In 1884, Hall showed that the position of the elliptical orbit of Saturn's moon, Hyperion, was retrograding by about 20° per year.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall also investigated stellar parallaxes and the positions of the stars in the Pleiades star cluster.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall was responsible for apprenticing Henry S.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Pritchett at the Naval Observatory in 1875.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] During Mars's closest approach in 1877, Hall was encouraged by Angeline Stickney, his wife, to search for the Martian moons.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] His calculations had shown that the orbit should be very close to the planet.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] At the time, he was deliberately searching for Martian moons.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall had previously seen what appeared to be a Martian moon on August 10, but due to bad weather, he could not definitively identify them until later.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] He became a lecturer in celestial mechanics at Harvard University in 1896, and continued to teach there until 1901.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] (1859–1930) became an astronomer, Samuel Stickney Hall (1864–1936) worked for Mutual Life Insurance Company, Angelo Hall (1868–1922) became a Unitarian minister and professor of mathematics at the US Naval Academy, and Percival Hall (1872–1953) became president of Gallaudet University.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall married Mary Gauthier after he fully retired to Goshen, Connecticut in 1901.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall died in November 1907 while visiting his son Angelo in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society in 1878.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] He won the Lalande Prize of the French Academy of Sciences in 1878, the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1879, the Arago Medal in 1893, and was made a Chevalier in the Ordre national de la Légion d'honneur (French Legion of Honor) in 1896.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] In 1885, he was President of the Philosophical Society of Washington.
[src:asaph-hall/asaph-hall] Hall crater on the Moon as well as Hall crater on the Martian moon Phobos are named in his honor.
